A stack is a data structure that follows the Last In First Out (LIFO) principle. It consists of a sequence of objects, with one object visible at any given time. You can push and pop elements onto and from the stack. Pushing an element adds it to the top of the stack, while popping removes the top element. 

A queue is a data structure that follows the First In First Out (FIFO) principle. It consists of a sequential set of objects, where one object is visible at a time. You can enqueue and dequeue elements onto and from the queue. Enqueuing an element adds it to the back of the queue, while dequeuing removes the front element. 

