1. Bubble Sort: This algorithm sorts an array by repeatedly swapping the adjacent elements if they are in wrong order. The time complexity of bubble sort is O(n^2), which means that the number of swaps required increases quadratically with the length of the array.
```
void bubbleSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < n - i - 1; j++) {
            if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
                int temp = arr[j];
                arr[j] = arr[j + 1];
                arr[j + 1] = temp;
            }
        }
    }
}
```
2. Insertion Sort: This algorithm sorts an array by inserting the missing elements into their correct positions. The time complexity of insertion sort is O(n^2), but the number of comparisons required decreases from n to 1 as the sorting progresses.
```
void insertionSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
        int key = arr[i];
        int j = i - 1;
        while (j >= 0 && arr[j] < key) {
            arr[j + 1] = arr[j];
            j--;
        }
        arr[j + 1] = key;
    }
}
